    // Methodology
    methPageTitle: "Our Methodology",
    methPageDesc: "Why our taekwondo-specific training logic produces better athletes than generic programs.",
    methHeroTitle: "Why our taekwondo logic is better",
    methHeroSubtitle: "Most training programs are built for general fitness or classical strength training. Taekwondo demands something different.",
    methWhyTitle: "Built for taekwondo — not adapted from fitness",
    methWhyBody: "Our logic is developed from the actual demands of taekwondo: explosiveness, reaction, mobility, repeated high-intensity actions, kick control, the ability to maintain quality late in a fight, and the balance between technical training and physical development. The program is not just 'strength alongside taekwondo'. It's built to support the sport — not disrupt it.",
    methAdaptTitle: "How the program adapts to fight load",
    methAdaptBody: "In taekwondo, it makes no sense to train the same every week. The load changes depending on sparring, technical sessions, competitions, weight management, and recovery. That's why the program adapts to the athlete's real week:",
    methAdaptList1: "How many taekwondo sessions there are",
    methAdaptList2: "How hard the sessions are",
    methAdaptList3: "Whether it's sparring or technical focus",
    methAdaptList4: "How close to a fight or competition",
    methAdaptList5: "Whether the body is stressed or ready for high load",
    methAdaptOutro: "This means the strength and conditioning portion is adjusted to fight load, so the athlete doesn't get overloaded or show up tired for the most important sessions.",
    methSparTitle: "Sparring, recovery, and explosiveness",
    methSparIntro: "Sparring is a load in itself. Many programs ignore this and add heavy training on top, as if the athlete isn't already pushing their body hard several times a week. That's a classic mistake. Our approach accounts for three things simultaneously:",
    methSparSparring: "Sparring",
    methSparSparringBody: "When a week includes hard sparring, the physical training is adjusted so it supports performance instead of draining the legs and lowering quality.",
    methSparRecovery: "Recovery",
    methSparRecoveryBody: "The program plans not just load, but also when the body should absorb training. This reduces the risk of the athlete constantly training tired, heavy, and half-ready.",
    methSparExplosive: "Explosiveness",
    methSparExplosiveBody: "Taekwondo isn't just about getting stronger — it's about converting strength into speed, timing, and power. That's why the program prioritizes explosive qualities and movements that deliver value in the fight — not just more kilos on the bar.",
    methErrorTitle: "Reducing programming errors for TKD athletes",
    methErrorIntro: "One of the biggest challenges for taekwondo athletes is poor programming. This typically happens when you:",
    methErrorList1: "Train too heavy too close to sparring",
    methErrorList2: "Build too much leg fatigue",
    methErrorList3: "Use bodybuilding logic instead of combat sport logic",
    methErrorList4: "Overlook recovery",
    methErrorList5: "Train 'hard' without considering timing and total weekly load",
    methErrorOutro: "Our program reduces these errors by considering the whole picture. It doesn't treat physical training as something isolated — but as part of the athlete's total performance.",
    methResultsTitle: "What results it creates",
    methResultsIntro: "When the program is built correctly for taekwondo, you typically see better results where it actually matters:",
    methResultsList1: "More explosiveness in kicks and movements",
    methResultsList2: "Better quality in sparring over longer periods",
    methResultsList3: "Less unnecessary fatigue in legs and hips",
    methResultsList4: "Better balance between strength, speed, and mobility",
    methResultsList5: "More stable development without the body constantly feeling heavy",
    methResultsList6: "Greater likelihood of peaking for fights and competitions",
    methResultsOutro: "It doesn't just create a stronger athlete in the gym. It creates an athlete better prepared to perform on the mat.",
    methCta: "Our Methodology",
